  footnotes: []
english:
  title: The Daedong River
  author: Kim Yeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Clouds part from the endless sky as water mirrors heaven.
    Atop the Daedong Tower, a splendid feast unfolds.
    Clear sunlight filters through the hanging curtains,
    And fragrant mist drifts upon the strings and pipes.

    One long river runs crystal clear as a mirror,
    While two rows of weeping willows fade into distant mist.
    Beholding the landscape before Eulmilar Tower,
    I mark what ten years of witnessing foretells of things to come.
  footnotes:
    - 'Daedong Tower (대동루): A historical pavilion overlooking the Daedong River in Pyongyang, North Korea, known as a site of cultural refinement and entertainment.'
    - 'Eulmilar Tower (을밀대): Another historical structure in Pyongyang, significant in Korean cultural heritage.'
    - The poem employs the mirror metaphor to suggest both reflection and prophecy—the river reflects the present moment while the speaker's observations reflect upon the future.
